The cabinet shall issue a certification as a radon measurement contractor to any person who:
Submits a complete and accurate application for certification on a form prescribed by the cabinet through promulgation of an administrative regulation;
Pays the certification fee established by the cabinet through promulgation of an administrative regulation within the following restrictions:
An initial certification fee shall not exceed two hundred fifty dollars ($250);
An annual renewal fee shall not exceed two hundred fifty dollars ($250);
A duplicate certificate fee shall not exceed twenty dollars ($20); and
A late renewal fee shall not exceed one hundred dollars ($100);
Provides the cabinet with documentation of successful completion of a cabinet-approved radon measurement course and exam;
For renewal of certification, provides proof of completion of at least eight (8) hours of continuing education per year;
Submits a quality control program plan that meets the minimum standard operating procedures requirements as established by the cabinet through promulgation of an administrative regulation; and
Furnishes evidence of financial responsibility to the cabinet consisting of a liability insurance policy that satisfies the requirements of KRS 211.9113.

A measurement contractor shall:
Ensure all measurements are conducted in accordance with the measurement standard operating procedures established by the cabinet through promulgation of an administrative regulation;
Maintain a quality control program plan that meets the minimum standard operating procedures requirements established by the cabinet through promulgation of an administrative regulation;
Ensure all measurement activities are conducted under the general supervision of an individual certified to conduct radon measurement;
Use or sell only cabinet-approved devices to conduct radon measurement; and
Ensure all services procured from a radon laboratory are procured from a radon laboratory certified by the cabinet.
